Matthis wondered how many more dawns he would see before he died. The peaks of Blackvein turned a chilly blue that blocked the watery orange sun. Miners and bread makers rose earliest, but children reacted to the uncaged corpse first. A group of them charged toward Matthis, saw what stood next to him, and shriveled. They whimpered and ran back to the square yelling, "Bone man, bone man!" as though it were an alarm call for fire.

Matthis closed his eyes. A stiff breeze knocked at him, threatened to bend him. He squared himself and braced. He opened his eyes. His jaw clenched.

A procession of about thirty adults spotted him and advanced toward him. The Vicar led the way, flanked by Mercy. Matthias spotted Rafe, Bartholomew and Godric the mining wizards, Corven the Miner's Guild master with his usual mustache, and Elspeth. The wizard corpse did not move. It did not bend in the wind. It cocked its head. The group formed a semicircle twenty feet away.

Mercy shrieked, and he couldn't tell if she directed it at him or the undead wizard.

"You see? The Bone Man is a monster!"

Matthis lowered his eyes to the dusty ground. The wizard moaned. A man spat and swore. A woman whimpered and covered her face in her apron. Someone clasped their hands and gasped. Whispers leaked through the crowd. Bone Man. 

The Vicar's narrowed eyes did not blink. They trained on the undead corpse. The wizard did not move. It oozed. Black sludge fell and slopped on its boots. 

In the square, children played a game of chase. They dashed between buildings, far enough away to hear nothing. 

Corven stroked his moustache and closed his eyes. A miner retched.

"We should string him up from his own gallows!"

Pickaxes raised. A roar of approval. Arms uncrossed. One man stomped his feet, bloodlust in his eyes. 

Matthis hung his head. The wizard moaned.

"No!"

Every head turned. Elspeth clutched her heart, eyes on Matthis.

Rafe stepped in front of her.

"None of you know what he's done for this village. If you knew --"

"Enough." 

The Vicar's voice sliced through the crowd. A babe cried. Feet shuffled. A man rubbed his neck and looked away. Another shielded his eyes.

"Matthis," said the Vicar. "Explain this body. What happened?"

Every eye turned to Matthis. He opened his mouth. A brittle, dry croak came out. The crowd bristled. "He really is one of them," someone whispered. Bone Man. Bone Man. 

"I ... " he croaked. "I don't know."

"What about our children?" The woman with a baby shrieked. Her child wailed. "What will we do when it comes for them? We can't stop them! We can't let it happen again!" 

"It was you all along!" Mercy cried, her arm raised and pointing. "You were causing this from the start!"

One man pulled a coil of rope from his bag. Another bore his teeth and growled. Pickaxes rose over the crowd. 

Rafe and Elspeth's yells were drowned out by savage roars. The Vicar covered his eyes. 

"It was you!" Mercy screamed. "All along, you made them rise!"

The crowd rushed forward. The rope unraveled in someone's hands.

Pale light broke over Blackvein. It caressed his cheek. He would see the sun again. One last time.